    <p>Drottningholm Palace is the permanent private residence of the Swedish Royal Family and one of Sweden's most visited tourist sites. Located on the island of Lovön in Lake Mälaren, approximately 10 kilometres west of Stockholm's Gamla Stan, the palace was built from 1662 onward under the commission of Queen Hedvig Eleonora. Architect Nicodemus Tessin the Elder designed the main building in a style directly inspired by the Palace of Versailles and other French Baroque royal residences of the period. The palace was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1991 as the best-preserved Swedish royal palace from the 17th century.</p>
    <p>The southern wing of the palace is reserved as the private residence of Their Majesties the King and Queen. The remaining rooms, including the Royal Apartments, ceremonial halls, and the grand staircase, are open to the public year-round. The palace park, which includes both a formal Baroque garden and an English romantic landscape garden, is free to enter and open year-round. The Chinese Pavilion — an 18th-century pleasure palace in the park — is a separate ticketed attraction open from May to September. The Drottningholm Palace Theatre, dating from 1766, is one of the world's best-preserved 18th-century theatres; it retains its original stage machinery, painted backdrops, and Italian-style auditorium, and is still used for opera performances in summer.</p>
    <p>Guided tours of 45 minutes are available and can be booked through the official website. The palace is reachable by seasonal boat service from Klara Mälarstrand pier in central Stockholm (May–September, operated by Stromma) or by bus from Brommaplan metro station year-round. The palace may be partially closed during His Majesty the King's official receptions — check kungligaslotten.se for current closure dates before visiting. Conversion rate used: 1 SEK ≈ €0.087 (March 2026). Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
