  <div class="sec">
    <div class="sec-t">FAQ</div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How much does Drottningholm Palace cost in 2026?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Adult SEK 170 (approx. €15.00). Student SEK 150 (approx. €13.00). Children aged 7–17 SEK 85 (approx. €7.50). Children under 7 free when accompanied by an adult. A combined ticket for the palace and the Chinese Pavilion costs SEK 250 (approx. €21.50) for adults. Buy tickets at kungligaslotten.actorsmartbook.se or at the entrance desk on site.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What are Drottningholm Palace opening hours in 2026?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">January 10–April 30 and October 1–December 6: Saturday–Sunday 10:00–16:00. May–September: daily 10:00–17:00. December 7–30: closed. New Year period (December 31–January 6): daily 10:00–16:00. The palace can be partially closed during His Majesty the King's official receptions — check kungligaslotten.se before visiting.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How do I get to Drottningholm Palace from Stockholm?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">By boat: a seasonal boat service operates from Klara Mälarstrand pier (between Stockholm Central Station and City Hall) from May to September, operated by Stromma. By bus: take bus 177 or 178 from Brommaplan metro station (green line T10) to Drottningholm. Travel time by bus is approximately 30 minutes from the city centre.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is the palace park at Drottningholm free?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. The palace park — including both the Baroque garden and the English romantic landscape park — is free to enter and open year-round. The Chinese Pavilion within the park is a separate ticketed attraction open May–September at SEK 140 adult (approx. €12.00), or combined with the palace at SEK 250 adult (approx. €21.50). Book at kungligaslotten.actorsmartbook.se.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is Drottningholm Palace a UNESCO World Heritage Site?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. Drottningholm Palace was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1991. It is recognised as the most well-preserved royal palace from the 17th century in Sweden. The World Heritage designation covers the palace, the Chinese Pavilion, the Court Theatre, and the palace park.</div>
    </div>
